# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1802-united-kingdom-general-election] The **1802 United Kingdom general election** was the first general election after the Acts of Union 1800, held from 5 July 1802 to 28 August 1802, to elect members of the House of Commons, the lower house of the new Parliament of the United Kingdom.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1802-united-kingdom-general-election] The first Parliament had been composed of members of the former Parliaments of the Kingdom of Great Britain and the Kingdom of Ireland.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1802-united-kingdom-general-election] The Parliament of Great Britain held its last general election in 1796.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1802-united-kingdom-general-election] The final election for the Parliament of Ireland was held in 1797.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1802-united-kingdom-general-election] The first united Parliament was dissolved on 29 June 1802.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1802-united-kingdom-general-election] The new Parliament was summoned to meet on 31 August 1802, for a maximum seven-year term from that date.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1802-united-kingdom-general-election] Prime Minister Henry Addington led a war-time administration of pro-government Whigs and Tories, collectively referred to as the "Addingtonians", in office during part of the Napoleonic Wars.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1802-united-kingdom-general-election] The previous Prime Minister, William Pitt the Younger, had been out of office since 1801.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1802-united-kingdom-general-election] King George III had forced Pitt to resign by refusing to agree to Catholic emancipation (allowing Catholics to sit in Parliament) following the Union.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1802-united-kingdom-general-election] His faction in Parliament was generally supportive of the Addington ministry, before becoming increasingly opposed over the course of the Parliamentary term.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1802-united-kingdom-general-election] On 25 March 1802 the Treaty of Amiens brought about peace with France, with which Great Britain had been at war since 1792.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1802-united-kingdom-general-election] The international situation remained uneasy and a renewal of war was still possible.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1802-united-kingdom-general-election] The Treaty was supported by a strong majority of the Commons, only meeting strong opposition from the small group of 'New Opposition' or Grenvillite parliamentarians, formed around Lord Grenville and led in the Commons by William Windham, both former cabinet ministers under Pitt.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1802-united-kingdom-general-election] In the election the combination of the followers of Addington and Pitt comfortably defeated both the 'Old' Opposition Foxites under Charles James Fox and the 'New' Opposition of Lord Grenville.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1802-united-kingdom-general-election] Despite his reluctance to foster a personal faction and the presence of some of his followers in both support and opposition to Addington, Pitt retained an unclear personal following of around fifty-seven MPs.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1802-united-kingdom-general-election] The election was a decidedly quiet affair owing to the general popularity of Addington's diplomatic and peace policies.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1802-united-kingdom-general-election] Two notable results occurred in the urban constituencies of Middlesex and Norwich.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1802-united-kingdom-general-election] At Middlesex the Radical Francis Burdett defeated William Mainwaring, a supporter of Addington.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1802-united-kingdom-general-election] After an inquiry Burdett was unseated and defeated narrowly at a by-election by Mainwaring's son, George Boulton Mainwaring.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1802-united-kingdom-general-election] At Norwich Windham and fellow conservative incumbent John Frere were defeated by Radical William Smith and Foxite Robert Fellowes in a campaign where Windham's opposition to peace had weakened his popularity.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1802-united-kingdom-general-election] Windham was promptly returned for St Mawes, a pocket borough of Lord Grenville's brother, Lord Buckingham.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1802-united-kingdom-general-election] At this period there was not one election day.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1802-united-kingdom-general-election] After receiving a writ (a royal command) for the election to be held, the local returning officer fixed the election timetable for the particular constituency or constituencies he was concerned with.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1802-united-kingdom-general-election] Polling in seats with contested elections could continue for many days.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1802-united-kingdom-general-election] The election took place over a period of almost two months.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1802-united-kingdom-general-election] The time between the first and last contested elections was 5 July to 28 August 1802.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1802-united-kingdom-general-election] Monmouthshire (1 County constituency with 2 MPs and one single member Borough constituency) is included in Wales in these tables.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1802-united-kingdom-general-election] Sources for this period may include the county in England.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1806-united-kingdom-general-election] The **1806 United Kingdom general election** was the second general election after the Acts of Union 1800, held from 29 October 1806 to 17 December 1806, to elect members of the House of Commons, the lower house of Parliament.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1806-united-kingdom-general-election] The general election took place in a situation of considerable uncertainty about the future of British politics, following the sudden death of William Pitt the Younger and the formation of the Ministry of all the Talents.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1806-united-kingdom-general-election] Parliament was dissolved on 24 October 1806.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1806-united-kingdom-general-election] The new Parliament was summoned to meet on 13 December 1806, for a maximum seven-year term from that date.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1806-united-kingdom-general-election] The maximum term could be and normally was curtailed, by the monarch dissolving the Parliament, before its term expired.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1806-united-kingdom-general-election] Since the previous general election fighting in the Napoleonic Wars with France had resumed in 1803.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1806-united-kingdom-general-election] Tory Prime Minister Henry Addington had resigned in 1804.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1806-united-kingdom-general-election] William Pitt the Younger formed a new coalition of pro-government Whig and Tory politicians to prosecute the war.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1806-united-kingdom-general-election] The opposition Whigs, led by Charles James Fox, continued to oppose the government.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1806-united-kingdom-general-election] They were strengthened by a group of Pitt's former supporters (such as his cousin William Grenville, 1st Baron Grenville) who had aligned themselves with Fox in opposition to Addington after 1802 and who did not accompany Pitt and his other friends back to office in 1804.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1806-united-kingdom-general-election] When Pitt died on 23 January 1806 a new ministry was formed by Grenville.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1806-united-kingdom-general-election] It included Fox and Addington (now ennobled as the 1st Viscount Sidmouth) as well as other leading political figures of the day.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1806-united-kingdom-general-election] However it did not include George Canning, who had inherited the leadership of Pitt's faction in the House of Commons or the Duke of Portland who led it in the House of Lords.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1806-united-kingdom-general-election] This government was known as the Ministry of all the Talents.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1806-united-kingdom-general-election] An attempt was made to end the Napoleonic Wars by negotiation.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1806-united-kingdom-general-election] Grenville also tried to strengthen the government, but was unable to persuade the Pittites to join him either as a body or by detaching some leading figures.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1806-united-kingdom-general-election] The Prime Minister was not prepared to exclude Fox and his friends as the Pittites wanted.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1806-united-kingdom-general-election] Lord Grenville then decided to hold a general election to strengthen his government.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1806-united-kingdom-general-election] The Talents were in office at the time of this election and continued after it, but the Ministry was weakened by the death of Fox on 13 September 1806.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1806-united-kingdom-general-election] The election itself was a disappointment.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1806-united-kingdom-general-election] In the eighteenth century a government with the King's backing could expect to make substantial gains at an election.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1806-united-kingdom-general-election] However Pitt's financial reforms had weakened the ability of the Treasury to manipulate election results.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1806-united-kingdom-general-election] Foord estimated that the Ministry only gained about thirty seats by the 1806 appeal to the country.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1806-united-kingdom-general-election] The time between the first and last contested elections was 29 October to 17 December 1806.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1807-united-kingdom-general-election] The **1807 United Kingdom general election** was the third general election after the Acts of Union 1800, held from 4 May 1807 to 9 June 1807.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1807-united-kingdom-general-election] The third United Kingdom Parliament was dissolved on 29 April 1807.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1807-united-kingdom-general-election] The new Parliament was summoned to meet on 22 June 1807, for a maximum seven-year term from that date.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1807-united-kingdom-general-election] Following the 1806 election the Ministry of all the Talents, a coalition of the Foxite and Grenvillite Whig and Addingtonite Tory factions, with William Grenville, 1st Baron Grenville, as Prime Minister continued in office.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1807-united-kingdom-general-election] It had attempted to end the Napoleonic Wars by negotiation.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1807-united-kingdom-general-election] The faction formerly led by William Pitt the Younger, before his death in January 1806, were the major group in opposition to the Talents' Ministry.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1807-united-kingdom-general-election] George Canning in the House of Commons and the Duke of Portland in the House of Lords were at the head of this opposition.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1807-united-kingdom-general-election] Grenville and his cabinet lost the support of King George III by trying to legislate to permit Roman Catholics to serve as Army and Navy officers.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1807-united-kingdom-general-election] When ministers refused to give the King written confirmation that they would not raise the Catholic issue again, he decided to find new servants.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1807-united-kingdom-general-election] The elderly Duke of Portland was asked to form a new ministry in March 1807.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1807-united-kingdom-general-election] Portland had been the Whig Prime Minister before, in the 1780s, so now he described himself as the Whig Prime Minister of a Tory ministry.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1807-united-kingdom-general-election] After Pitt's death the younger Pittites increasingly began calling themselves the Tory Party, whether they had previously belonged to the Whig or Tory tradition.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1807-united-kingdom-general-election] This was an important stage in the development of a more organised two-party system, which reduced the influence of factions and connections in British politics.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1807-united-kingdom-general-election] The new ministers found it difficult to manage a House of Commons recently elected to support their opponents.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1807-united-kingdom-general-election] A month into the new government the King granted a dissolution.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1807-united-kingdom-general-election] The government policies of opposing Catholic relief and supporting the traditional powers of the King proved popular (at least with the restricted section of the population enfranchised in elections for the unreformed House of Commons).
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1807-united-kingdom-general-election] After the election the government programme was approved by a vote of 350 to 155 in the House of Commons, demonstrating the substantial gains ministers had made in the election.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1807-united-kingdom-general-election] The time between the first and last contested elections was 4 May to 9 June 1807.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1812-united-kingdom-general-election] The **1812 United Kingdom general election** was the fourth general election after the Union of Great Britain and Ireland, held from 5 October 1812 to 10 November 1812, taking place at the height of the Napoleonic Wars.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1812-united-kingdom-general-election] The fourth United Kingdom Parliament was dissolved on 29 September 1812, four months after the Earl of Liverpool succeeded to the premiership following the assassination of Spencer Perceval.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1812-united-kingdom-general-election] The new Parliament was summoned to meet on 24 November 1812, for a maximum seven-year term from that date.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1812-united-kingdom-general-election] Following the 1807 election the Pittite Tory ministry, led as prime minister by the Duke of Portland (who still claimed to be a Whig), continued to prosecute the Napoleonic Wars.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1812-united-kingdom-general-election] At the core of the opposition were the Foxite Whigs, led since the death of Fox in 1806 by Earl Grey (known by the courtesy title of Viscount Howick and a member of the House of Commons from 1806 to 1807).
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1812-united-kingdom-general-election] However, as Foord observes: "the affairs of the party during most of this period were in a state of uncertainty and confusion".
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1812-united-kingdom-general-election] Grey was not the commanding leader Fox had been.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1812-united-kingdom-general-election] After Grey inherited his peerage and went to the House of Lords in 1807, the party leadership in the House of Commons was extremely weak.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1812-united-kingdom-general-election] The Grenvillites, associated with the Whig Prime Minister before Portland, William Grenville, 1st Baron Grenville, were also in opposition but were of less significance than the Foxites.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1812-united-kingdom-general-election] Despite this Grenville was recognised as the first Leader of the Opposition in the House of Lords.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1812-united-kingdom-general-election] A relative of Grey's wife, George Ponsonby, was proposed to Whig MPs by Grey and Grenville as the Whig leader in the House of Commons.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1812-united-kingdom-general-election] Ponsonby was the first person recognised as the official Leader of *the* Opposition in the House of Commons, as opposed to the leader of *an* opposition faction.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1812-united-kingdom-general-election] He proved to be incompetent but could not be persuaded to resign.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1812-united-kingdom-general-election] Until 1812 the Tory faction associated with another former prime minister, Henry Addington, 1st Viscount Sidmouth, and were also out of office.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1812-united-kingdom-general-election] The smallest component of the opposition were the Radicals, who were a largely middle-class group of reformers.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1812-united-kingdom-general-election] They had philosophical differences with the more aristocratic Whigs, but usually ended up voting with them in Parliament.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1812-united-kingdom-general-election] In 1809 Portland, whose health was failing, resigned.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1812-united-kingdom-general-election] The new Tory Prime Minister was Spencer Perceval.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1812-united-kingdom-general-election] In April 1812 he brought Sidmouth into the cabinet.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1812-united-kingdom-general-election] A month later, on 11 May 1812, Perceval was assassinated.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1812-united-kingdom-general-election] The premiership passed to the Earl of Liverpool, who failed to attract Grenville.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1812-united-kingdom-general-election] This was a further stage in the development of a two-party system—just about all Tories supported the government and all Whigs opposed it.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1812-united-kingdom-general-election] The general election of 1812 returned the Tories to power for another term.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1812-united-kingdom-general-election] An example of what happened in the 1812 election was the Irish constituency of Westmeath.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1812-united-kingdom-general-election] Walker confirms the date of election was 24 October 1812.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1812-united-kingdom-general-election] Stooks Smith indicates that there were three days of polling, during which time 950 electors came to the hustings and voted.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1812-united-kingdom-general-election] The polling in the Berkshire election of 1812 went on for 15 days (with 1,992 electors voting).
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1812-united-kingdom-general-election] The time between the first and last contests in the general election was 5 October to 10 November 1812.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1818-united-kingdom-general-election] The **1818 United Kingdom general election** was the 5th general election after the Acts of Union 1800, held on 17 June 1818 to 18 July 1818.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1818-united-kingdom-general-election] It saw the Whigs gain a few seats, but the Tories under the Earl of Liverpool retained a majority of around 90 seats.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1818-united-kingdom-general-election] The Whigs were divided over their response to growing social unrest and the introduction of the Corn Laws.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1818-united-kingdom-general-election] The fifth United Kingdom Parliament was dissolved on 10 June 1818.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1818-united-kingdom-general-election] The new Parliament was summoned to meet on 4 August 1818, for a maximum seven-year term from that date.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1818-united-kingdom-general-election] The sixth Parliament lasted only about a year and a half, as King George III's death on 29 January 1820 triggered a dissolution of Parliament.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1818-united-kingdom-general-election] The Tory leader was the Earl of Liverpool, who had been prime minister since his predecessor's assassination in 1812.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1818-united-kingdom-general-election] The Tory Leader of the House of Commons was Robert Stewart, Viscount Castlereagh.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1818-united-kingdom-general-election] The Whig Party had long suffered from weak leadership, particularly in the House of Commons.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1818-united-kingdom-general-election] At the time of the general election, the Earl Grey was the leading figure amongst the Whig peers.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1818-united-kingdom-general-election] The last Whig Prime Minister, the Lord Grenville, had retired from active politics in 1817.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1818-united-kingdom-general-election] It was likely that Earl Grey would have been invited to form a government, had the Whigs come to power, although in this era the monarch rather than the governing party decided which individual would be prime minister.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1818-united-kingdom-general-election] The Leader of the Opposition in the House of Commons, until his death in 1817, was George Ponsonby, Lady Grey's uncle.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1818-united-kingdom-general-election] About a year after Ponsonby's death, George Tierney reluctantly became the recognised Leader of the Opposition in the House of Commons.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1818-united-kingdom-general-election] However, after 1819 he did not carry out the functions of leader although he retained the title.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1820-united-kingdom-general-election] The **1820 United Kingdom general election** was held on 6 March 1820 to 14 April 1820, to elect members of the House of Commons, the lower house of Parliament.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1820-united-kingdom-general-election] Triggered by the death of King George III, it produced the first parliament of the reign of his successor, King George IV.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1820-united-kingdom-general-election] It was held shortly after the Radical War in Scotland and the Cato Street Conspiracy.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1820-united-kingdom-general-election] In this atmosphere, the Tories under the Earl of Liverpool were able to win a substantial majority over the Whigs.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1820-united-kingdom-general-election] The sixth United Kingdom Parliament was dissolved on 29 February 1820.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1820-united-kingdom-general-election] The new Parliament was summoned to meet on 21 April 1820, for a maximum seven-year term from that date.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1820-united-kingdom-general-election] The maximum term could be and normally was curtailed, by the monarch dissolving the Parliament before its term expired.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1820-united-kingdom-general-election] Liverpool had led his party to two general election victories before that of 1820.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1820-united-kingdom-general-election] The Whig Party continued to suffer from weak leadership, particularly in the House of Commons.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1820-united-kingdom-general-election] It was likely that Grey would have been invited to form a government, had the Whigs come to power, although in this era the monarch rather than the governing party decided which individual would be prime minister.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1820-united-kingdom-general-election] The Leader of the Opposition in the House of Commons, George Tierney, was successful at first after the Whig gains at the 1818 general election.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1820-united-kingdom-general-election] However, on 18 May 1819, Tierney moved a motion in the House of Commons for a committee on the state of the nation.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1820-united-kingdom-general-election] Foord comments that "this defeat put an effective end to Tierney's leadership".
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1820-united-kingdom-general-election] However he continued to be the nominal leader at the time of the 1820 election.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1820-united-kingdom-general-election] It was triggered by the death of King George III.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1820-united-kingdom-general-election] The general election took place between the first contest on 6 March and the last contest on 14 April 1820.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1826-united-kingdom-general-election] The **1826 United Kingdom general election** was the 7th general election after the Acts of Union 1800, held on 7 June 1826 to 12 July 1826, to elect members of the House of Commons, the lower house of Parliament.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1826-united-kingdom-general-election] It saw the Tories under the Earl of Liverpool win a landslide victory over the Whigs.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1826-united-kingdom-general-election] In Ireland, liberal Protestant candidates favouring Catholic emancipation, backed by the Catholic Association, achieved significant gains.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1826-united-kingdom-general-election] The seventh United Kingdom Parliament was dissolved on 2 June 1826.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1826-united-kingdom-general-election] The new Parliament was summoned to meet on 25 July 1826, for a maximum seven-year term from that date.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1826-united-kingdom-general-election] As of 2024, the Earl of Liverpool remains the most recent prime minister to have won four successive elections.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1826-united-kingdom-general-election] Liverpool had led his party to three general election victories before that of 1826.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1826-united-kingdom-general-election] The Tory Leader of the House of Commons until 1822, when he committed suicide, was Robert Stewart.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1826-united-kingdom-general-election] He was known by the courtesy title of Viscount Castlereagh, until he inherited his father's Irish peerage and became the 2nd Marquess of Londonderry in 1821.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1826-united-kingdom-general-election] Londonderry was replaced as leader by George Canning, who remained Leader of the House of Commons in 1826.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1826-united-kingdom-general-election] In 1824 the Earl Grey gave up the formal Whig leadership in the Lords, although he remained the most prominent Whig peer.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1826-united-kingdom-general-election] Grey asked his friends to look to the leadership of the Marquess of Lansdowne.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1826-united-kingdom-general-election] Although Lansdowne performed the functions of leader, he did not accept the title.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1826-united-kingdom-general-election] At the time of the general election, Grey was still the leading figure amongst the Whig peers.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1826-united-kingdom-general-election] It was likely that he would have been invited to form a government, had the Whigs come to power, although in this era the monarch rather than the governing party decided which individual would be prime minister.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1826-united-kingdom-general-election] The Leader of the Opposition in the House of Commons at the previous general election, George Tierney, disclaimed the leadership on 23 January 1821.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1826-united-kingdom-general-election] No new Whig leader emerged during the rest of the Parliament.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1826-united-kingdom-general-election] There had been significant developments in Irish politics since the 1820 general election.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1826-united-kingdom-general-election] Whilst Catholics in Ireland—who met the normal property qualifications—had been permitted to vote since before the Union, they were still not eligible to sit in the United Kingdom Parliament.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1826-united-kingdom-general-election] The right for Catholics to serve in Parliament was known as a measure of Catholic emancipation.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1826-united-kingdom-general-election] In 1823, Daniel O'Connell started a campaign for repeal of the Act of Union, and took Catholic Emancipation as his rallying call, establishing the Catholic Association.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1826-united-kingdom-general-election] From 1826, the Catholic Association began to support pro-emancipation candidates in elections.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1826-united-kingdom-general-election] The Association used its money and manpower to campaign for candidates to be elected into Parliament, to pressure the government from within to pass Catholic emancipation.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1826-united-kingdom-general-election] The general election took place between the first contest on 7 June and the last contest on 12 July 1826.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1826-united-kingdom-general-election] In 1821 the borough of Grampound in Cornwall was disenfranchised for corruption.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1826-united-kingdom-general-election] Its two seats were transferred to the county of Yorkshire, which from this general election became a four-seat constituency.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] The Labour Party's manifesto for the October 1974 general election had promised that the people would decide through the ballot box whether to remain in the EC.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] In a 1975 pamphlet, Prime Minister Harold Wilson said: "I ask you to use your vote.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] For it is *your* vote that will now decide.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] The Government will accept *your* verdict." The pamphlet also said: "Now the time has come for *you* to decide.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] The Government will accept your decision — whichever way it goes." The electorate expressed significant support for continued EC membership, with 67% in favour on a national turnout of 64%.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] It was also the only national referendum to be held on the UK's relationship with Europe until the 2016 referendum on continued EU membership.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] The February 1974 general election had yielded a Labour minority government, which went on to win a very small overall majority in the October 1974 general election.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] Labour pledged in its February 1974 manifesto to renegotiate the terms of British accession to the EC, and then to consult the public on whether Britain should remain in the EC on the new terms, if they were acceptable to the government.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] The EC heads of government agreed to a deal in Dublin on 11 March 1975; Wilson declared: "I believe that our renegotiation objectives have been substantially though not completely achieved", and said that the government would recommend a vote in favour of continued membership.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] On 9 April, the House of Commons voted by 396 to 170 to continue within the Common Market on the new terms.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] Along with these developments, the government drafted a Referendum Bill, to be moved in case of a successful renegotiation.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] The referendum debate and campaign was an unusual time in British politics and was the third national vote to be held in seventeen months.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] During the campaign, the Labour Cabinet was split and its members campaigned on each side of the question, an unprecedented breach of Cabinet collective responsibility.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] Most votes in the House of Commons in preparation for the referendum were only carried after opposition support, and the Government faced several defeats on technical issues such as the handling and format of the referendum counts.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] The referendum did temporarily achieve Harold Wilson's ambition to bring the divided Labour Party together on the European issue; however, eight years later, Labour's 1983 general election manifesto pledged withdrawal from the Communities.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] It also significantly strengthened the position of the pro-marketeer (later pro-Europe) politicians in the UK Parliament for the next thirty years; however, the issue of continued membership, despite the outcome of the referendum, was ultimately never resolved and remained contentious.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] In the decades that followed, successive UK governments integrated further into the European project by ratifying subsequent European treaties (in particular Maastricht and Lisbon) through Parliament but without any further public approval.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] The UK Government did however decide against adopting the euro after the pound was forced to withdraw from the European Exchange Rate Mechanism in 1992, in what became known as Black Wednesday.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] When the European Coal and Steel Community was instituted in 1952, the United Kingdom decided not to become a member.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] The UK was still absent when the Treaty of Rome was signed in 1957, creating the European Economic Community (the "Common Market").
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] However, in the late 1950s the Conservative government of Harold Macmillan dramatically changed its attitude, and appointed Edward Heath to submit an application and to lead negotiations for Britain to enter the Common Market.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] The application was made at a meeting of the European Communities (EC) in January 1963, but the French president Charles de Gaulle rebuffed and vetoed Britain's request.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] The 1970 general election saw all the major political parties commit to either membership or to negotiate with the European Communities.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] The Conservative manifesto for the election on the issue was committed to negotiating membership but not at any price.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] The Conservatives won a total of 330 seats (out of a total of 630) on 46.6% of the national vote share, gaining 77 seats, which gave them an unexpected overall majority of about 30 seats.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] Edward Heath became Prime Minister, and personally led many of the negotiations which began following the election; he struck up a friendship with the new French president Georges Pompidou, who oversaw the lifting of the veto and thus paved the way for UK membership.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] The debate itself took place between 21 and 28 October 1971, with the House of Commons debating directly whether or not the United Kingdom should become a member of the EC.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] Conservative MPs were given a free vote, Labour MPs were given a three-line whip to vote against the motion, and Liberal MPs were whipped into voting in favour of the motion.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] The House of Commons voted 356–244 in favour of the motion, a substantial majority of 112.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] Throughout this period, the Labour Party was divided, both on the substantive issue of EC accession and on the question of whether accession ought to be approved by referendum.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] In 1971 pro-Market figures such as Roy Jenkins, the Deputy Leader of the Labour Party, said a Labour government would have agreed to the terms of accession secured by the Conservatives.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] However, the National Executive Committee and the Labour Party Conference disapproved of the terms.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] In April 1972, the anti-EC Conservative MP Neil Marten tabled an amendment to the European Communities Bill, which called for a consultative referendum on entry.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] Labour had previously opposed a referendum, but the Shadow cabinet decided to support Marten's amendment.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] Jenkins resigned as Deputy Leader in opposition to the decision, and many Labour MPs abstained in the division.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] The United Kingdom joined the European Communities as a member state on 1 January 1973, along with Denmark and Ireland.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] The EC would later become the European Union.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] The initial euphoria and initial expectations of British membership after joining was very short lived as events in the Middle East would cause impacts which would be particularly felt within Britain.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] The Yom Kippur War would lead to an Oil embargo by Arab counties which would lead to the "Three Day working week" being introduced and would eventually lead to Edward Heath to call a snap election which would ultimately end his time as Prime Minister.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] At the February 1974 United Kingdom general election, the Labour Party manifesto promised renegotiation of the UK's terms of membership, to be followed by a consultative referendum on continued membership under the new terms if they were acceptable.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] Labour would become the largest party but were without an overall majority but managed to form a minority government.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] Within one month of coming into office, the minority Labour Government started the negotiations promised in its February manifesto on the basis set out in that document.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] This could be interpreted as including the option of an election in 1975.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] Labour managed to win a very small working majority in a second general election which was held in October that year, and had no need of another general election and the referendum was organised.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] This white paper was approved by the House of Commons.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] A Referendum Bill was introduced to the Commons on 26 March; at its second reading on 10 April, MPs voted 312–248 in favour.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] Prior to the Bill's passing, there was no procedure or legislation within the United Kingdom for holding any such plebiscite.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] The vote, the only nationwide plebiscite to be held in the UK during the 20th century, was of constitutional significance.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] Referendums had been widely opposed in the past, on the grounds that they violated the principle of parliamentary sovereignty.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] The first major referendum (i.e. one covering more than one local government area) to be held in any part of the UK had been the sovereignty referendum in Northern Ireland in 1973.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] How the votes were to be counted caused much division as the Bill went through Parliament.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] This proposal did not attract the wider support of the Labour Party or the other opposition parties; the Liberal Party favoured individual counts in each of the parliamentary constituencies, and tabled an amendment to this effect, but was defeated by 263 to 131 votes in the House of Commons.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] However, another amendment, tabled in the Commons by Labour MP Roderick MacFarquhar, sought to have separate counts for each administrative region (the post-1974 county council areas): this won cross-party support, and was carried by 272 to 155 votes.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] The Act did not specify any national supermajority of 'Yes' votes for approval of the terms.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] It received royal assent on 8 May 1975, just under a month before the vote took place.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] A simple **YES** / **NO** answer was permitted (to be marked with a single 'X').
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] The question that was used was one of the options in the Government white paper of February 1975, although during the passage of the Referendum Bill through Parliament, the Government agreed to add the words "Common Market" in brackets at the end of the question.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] The referendum was called in April 1975 after the renegotiation was formally concluded.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] Cabinet members would be allowed to publicly campaign against each other.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] In total, seven of the twenty-three members of the cabinet opposed EC membership.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] Wilson's solution was that ministers speaking in the House of Commons should reflect government policy (i.e. support for EC membership), but would be allowed to speak freely elsewhere, thus avoiding a mass dismissal of Cabinet ministers.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] In spite of this, one minister, Eric Heffer, was obliged to resign after speaking against EC membership in the House of Commons.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] The 'Yes' campaign was supported by Wilson and the majority of the cabinet, including the holders of the three other Great Offices of State: Denis Healey, the Chancellor of the Exchequer; James Callaghan, the Foreign Secretary; and Roy Jenkins, the Home Secretary.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] The influential Conservative Edward du Cann said that "the Labour party is hopelessly and irrevocably split and muddled over this issue".
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] The 'No' campaign included the left wing of the Labour Party, including the cabinet ministers Michael Foot, Tony Benn, Peter Shore, and Barbara Castle who during the campaign famously said "They lured us into the market with the mirage of the market miracle".
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] Some Labour 'No' supporters, including Eric Varley and Douglas Jay, were on the right wing of the party, but most were from the left.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] The 'No' campaign also included a large number of Labour backbenchers; upon the division on a pro-EC white paper about the renegotiation, 148 Labour MPs opposed their own government's measure, whereas only 138 supported it and 32 abstained.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] "Many Conservatives feel the European Community is not good for Britain ...
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] Most of the Ulster Unionist Party were for 'No' in the referendum, most prominently the former Conservative minister Enoch Powell, who after Benn was the second-most prominent anti-Marketeer in the campaign.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] Other parties supporting the 'No' campaign included the Democratic Unionist Party, the Scottish National Party, Plaid Cymru, and parties outside Parliament including the National Front and the Communist Party of Great Britain.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] Conservative and Liberal Party conferences consistently supported EC membership for several years up to 1975.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] At a Labour Party conference on 26 April 1975, the Labour membership rejected continuing EC membership by almost a 2:1 margin.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] Tony Benn said, "We have had a conference and the decision is clear ...
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] Prior to the conference, the party had decided that if the conference voted by a margin of 2:1 or more in favour of a particular option, it would then support that position in the referendum campaign.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] Otherwise, the 'party machine' would remain neutral.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] Therefore, the Labour Party itself did not campaign on either side.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] The government distributed pamphlets from the official Yes and No campaigns to every household in Britain, together with its own pamphlet which argued in support of EC membership.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] According to this pamphlet, "the most important (issues in the renegotiation) were FOOD and MONEY and JOBS".
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] During the campaign, almost the entire mainstream national British press supported the 'Yes' campaign.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] The left-wing *Morning Star* was the only notable national daily to back the 'No' campaign.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] Television broadcasts were used by both campaigns, like party political broadcasts during general elections.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] They were broadcast simultaneously on all three terrestrial channels: BBC 1, BBC 2 and ITV.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] They attracted audiences of up to 20 million viewers.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] The 'Yes' campaign advertisements were thought to be much more effective, showing their speakers listening to and answering people's concerns, while the 'No' campaign's broadcasts featured speakers reading from an autocue.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] The 'Yes' campaign enjoyed much more funding, thanks to the support of many British businesses and the Confederation of British Industry.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] According to the treasurer of the 'Yes' campaign, Alistair McAlpine, "The banks and big industrial companies put in very large sums of money".
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] At the time, business was "overwhelmingly pro-European", and Harold Wilson met several prominent industrialists to elicit support.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] It was common for pro-Europeans to convene across party and ideological lines with businessmen.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] John Mills, the national agent of the 'No' campaign, recalled: "We were operating on a shoe-string compared to the Rolls Royce operation on the other side".
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] However, it was also the case that many civil society groups supported the 'Yes' campaign, including the National Farmers Union and some trade unions.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] Much of the 'Yes' campaign focused on the credentials of its opponents.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] According to Alistair McAlpine, "The whole thrust of our campaign was to depict the anti-Marketeers as unreliable people – dangerous people who would lead you down the wrong path ...
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] His claims were ridiculed by the 'Yes' campaign and ministers; the *Daily Mirror* labelled Benn the "Minister of Fear", and other newspapers were similarly derisive.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] Ultimately, the 'No' campaign lacked a national leader with broad appeal.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] Voting in the referendum took place across the United Kingdom on Thursday 5 June between 07:00 and 22:00 BST.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] All counting areas started their counts the following day on Friday 6 June at 09:00 BST, and the final result was announced just before 23:00 BST by the Chief Counting Officer (CCO) Sir Philip Allen at Earls Court Exhibition Centre in London, after all 68 counting areas had declared their totals.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] With a national turnout of 64% across the United Kingdom, the target to secure a majority for the winning side was 12,951,598 votes.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] The result was a decisive endorsement of continued EC membership, which won by a huge majority of 8,908,508 votes (34.5%) over those who had voted to reject continued membership.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] In total, over two-thirds of voters supported continued EC membership.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] 67.2 per cent voted 'Yes' and 32.8 per cent voted 'No'.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] At council level, support for EC membership was positively correlated with support for the Conservative Party and with average income.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] In contrast, poorer areas that supported Labour gave less support to the question.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] Approval was well above 60% in almost every council area in England and also in Wales, with the strongly Labour-supporting Mid Glamorgan being the exception.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] Scotland and Northern Ireland gave less support to the question than the British average.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] Once the voting areas had declared, their results were then relayed to Sir Philip Allen, the Chief Counting Officer, who later declared the final result.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] All the counting areas within the United Kingdom returned large majority 'Yes' votes except for two Scottish regions, the Shetland Islands and the Western Isles, which returned majority votes in favour of 'No'.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] NOTE: Unusually for a referendum **Yes** was the no change (status quo) option.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] Roy Jenkins said: "It puts the uncertainty behind us.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] The result strengthened Harold Wilson's tactical position, by securing a further post-election public expression of support for his policies.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] According to Cook and Francis (1979), 'The left of his party had been appeased by the holding of a referendum, the right by its result'.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] Following the result, the Labour Party and British trade unions themselves joined European institutions, such as the Socialist Group in the European Parliament, to which they had been reluctant to commit before public approval of EC membership.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] In the House of Commons, the referendum result settled the issue of Europe for two years, until the debate about direct elections to the European Parliament began in 1977.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] On that occasion the relative difference of enthusiasm for membership was reversed, with England and Wales voting to leave, whilst Scotland, London and Northern Ireland voted to stay.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] At 11pm GMT on 31 January 2020, after 47 years of membership, the United Kingdom left the European Union.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] Both the BBC and ITV provided coverage throughout the following day, and the BBC programme was presented by David Dimbleby and David Butler.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] There were several programmes throughout the day.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] While ITV's coverage was mixed in with live Horse Racing coverage from Epsom of the Epsom Oaks day card and was presented by Robert Kee and Peter Jay.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] This was the only major UK poll in which Alastair Burnet was not involved in the TV coverage as lead presenter as he was editing the Daily Express at the time of the referendum and was taking a break from broadcasting.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] The BBC only kept two hours of coverage - that shown between 2pm and 4pm although even by then the outcome was very clear - and that coverage was repeated on BBC Parliament to mark the 30th anniversary of the referendum in June 2005.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] It was also reshown to mark the 40th anniversary in June 2015 on the BBC Parliament channel, and was also shown again to mark the 41st anniversary, ahead of the 2016 EU Referendum.
[src:1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum/1975-united-kingdom-european-communities-membership-referendum] 41 years after the 1975 referendum, David Dimbleby also hosted the BBC's coverage as the UK voted to leave the EU.
